{{Multiple issues| {{more citations needed|date=January 2009}} {{original research|date=July 2012}} {{more footnotes|date=July 2012}} }}
The title of the "'''largest [[naval battle]] in history'''" is disputed between adherents of different criteria which include the numbers of personnel and/or vessels involved in the battle, and the total tonnage of the vessels involved. While battles fought in modern times are comparatively well-documented, the figures from those in pre-Renaissance times are generally believed to be exaggerated by contemporary chroniclers.
==The candidates== * '''[[Battle of Salamis|Salamis]]''', September (28?) 480 BC. 371 [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] ships defeated 300–600 [[Achaemenid Empire|Persian]] ships in this decisive battle. Greek [[trireme]]s had a crew of about 200 while their small [[Penteconter (ship)|penteconters]] had 50 oarsmen. * '''[[Battle of Cape Ecnomus|Cape Ecnomus]]''', 256 BC. One of [[Roman Republic|Rome's]] first major naval victories over its rival, the city of [[Ancient Carthage|Carthage]], in the [[First Punic War]]. The battle itself involved around 680 ships and 300,000 personnel from both sides. Total casualties were about 40,000–50,000, of which roughly 10,000 were on the Roman side and the rest from the Carthaginian side. *'''[[Battle of Red Cliffs|Red Cliffs]]''', winter of 208 AD. A decisive naval engagement between the forces of [[Cao Cao]] and the allied forces of [[Liu Bei]] and [[Sun Quan]], this battle resulted in the defeat of Cao Cao and confirmed the separation of China into northern and southern halves, the [[Yangtze River valley|Yangtze River Valley]] as a border. Between 270,000 and 850,000 personnel participated in this battle. *'''[[Battle of the Masts]]''', 654 AD. The Battle of the Masts, or the Battle of [[Finike]] (Phoenix), was an engagement involving the [[Byzantine Empire]], with 500 ships and led personally by Emperor [[Constans II]], and the newly formed navy of the [[Rashidun Caliphate]], commanded by Admiral [[Abu'l-Awar]], with 200 ships. The Byzantines hastily attacked, resulting in a decisive victory for the Arabs. Emperor Constans II barely escaped with his life, and this battle marked the emergence of Arabs on the Mediterranean. * '''[[Battle of Yamen|Yamen]]''', March 19, 1279. The battle which ended the Mongol-led [[Yuan Dynasty]]'s conquest of [[Southern Song Dynasty]]. It is claimed that more than 1,000 [[Song Dynasty]] warships were destroyed by the [[Yuan Dynasty]] near Yamen, [[Guangdong]], China. * '''[[Battle of Lake Poyang|Lake Poyang]]''', August 30&ndash;October 4, 1363. Claimed to be the largest naval battle in terms of personnel, with a reported 850,000 sailors and soldiers involved. A [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] rebel force, said to be 200,000 strong, commanded by [[Zhu Yuanzhang]], met a [[Han (people)|Han]] rebel force, claimed to be 650,000-strong, commanded by [[Chen Youliang]], on [[Lake Poyang]], China's largest freshwater lake. * '''[[Battle of Jutland|Jutland]]''', May 31&ndash;June 1, 1916. The Imperial German Navy's [[High Seas Fleet]] commanded by Vice-Admiral [[Reinhard Scheer]] and the British [[Grand Fleet]] under [[John Jellicoe, 1st Earl Jellicoe|Admiral Sir John Jellicoe]] engaged in battle near Jutland, Denmark during World War I. The German fleet consisted of 16 [[dreadnought]] and 6 [[Pre-dreadnought battleship|pre-dreadnought]] battleships, 5 [[Battlecruiser|battle cruisers]], 11 [[light cruiser]]s, and 61 fleet torpedo boats, while the numerically superior British fleet was composed of 28 battleships, 9 battle cruisers, 8 [[Armored cruiser|armoured cruisers]], 26 light cruisers, 78 destroyers, 1 [[minelayer]], and 1 [[Seaplane tender|seaplane carrier]]. Britain lost more ships and twice as many men as Germany, although ultimately the outcome was beneficial for the British as the battle resulted in the successful containment of the German fleet. In terms of total tonnage of ships involved, this was the largest surface battle.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Largest Naval Sea Battles in Military History|url=http://militaryhistory.norwich.edu/largest-naval-sea-battles-in-military-history/|website=Norwich University|accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref> * '''[[Battle of the Philippine Sea|Philippine Sea]]''', June 19–20, 1944. The largest aircraft carrier battle in history, involving fifteen U.S. [[Fleet carrier|fleet]] and [[Light aircraft carrier|light carriers]], nine Japanese carriers, 170 other warships and some 1,700 aircraft. In terms of tonnage, the U.S. Fifth Fleet's [[Task Force 58]] is the largest single naval formation ever to give battle. * '''[[Battle of Leyte Gulf|Leyte Gulf]]''', October 23&ndash;26, 1944. The largest in terms of [[tonnage]] of ships in the combined orders of battle, if not necessarily in terms of tonnage of the ships engaged; it is also the largest in terms of the tonnage of ships sunk, and in terms of the size of the area within which the component battles took place. The [[United States]] [[U.S. Third Fleet|Third]] and [[U.S. Seventh Fleet|Seventh]] Fleets, including some [[Royal Australian Navy|Australian]] warships, comprised 8 large [[aircraft carrier]]s, 8 [[light aircraft carrier|light carriers]], 18 [[escort carrier]]s, 12 [[Battleship#World War II|battleship]]s, 24 [[cruiser]]s, 141 [[destroyer]]s and [[destroyer escort]]s, many other ships, and around 1,500 aircraft. They won a decisive victory over [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] forces, which consisted of 1 large [[aircraft carrier]], 3 [[light aircraft carrier|light carriers]], nine battleships, 19 cruisers, 34 destroyers and several hundred aircraft. The opposing fleets carried a total of about 200,000 personnel. Leyte Gulf consisted of four major subsidiary battles: [[Battle of Leyte Gulf#Battle of the Sibuyan Sea (24 October)|Battle of the Sibuyan Sea]], [[Battle of Leyte Gulf#Battle of Surigao Strait (25 October)|Battle of Surigao Strait]], [[Battle of Samar]] and [[Battle of Leyte Gulf#Battle of Cape Engaño (25–26 October)|Battle of Cape Engano]], along with other actions. These are counted together by virtue of their all being caused by the Japanese operation ''Sho-Go'', which was aimed at destroying the Allied amphibious forces involved in the [[Battle of Leyte|invasion of Leyte]]. However, the individual battles were separated by distances as great as two hundred miles, as well as several days time, from the first submarine action to the Japanese withdrawal.
